{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511972"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11821"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11821"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.15,0.23,0.06,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61443"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46894"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1620"},{"type":"tags","id":"1692"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44364"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61443"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department (ED) with an open wound on his right arm three hours after fixing an old fence post in the paddock sustained during his work as a farmer. The patient states that he was fully vaccinated as a child and his last tetanus booster was six years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has a 6 cm laceration that is heavily contaminated with splinters and dirt and with subcutaneous fat on view. The plan is to perform wound debridement, wash-out, primary closure and to discharge from ED with General Practitioner follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to wound debridement, which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cefazolin 2 g IV TDS","Flucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID","Tetanus Immunoglobulin and Flucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID","Adsorbed diphtheria and tetanus (ADT) vaccine and Tetanus Immunoglobulin","Adsorbed diphtheria and tetanus (ADT) vaccine and Flucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdsorbed diphtheria and tetanus (ADT) vaccine and Flucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate response. Prophylactic antibiotic therapy is recommended for a contaminated wound such as this. In addition, as this is a large, dirty wound and it has been more than 5 years since his last tetanus dose, an ADT vaccine would be indicated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn regards to tetanus prophylaxis, the type of wound determines at what interval a tetanus booster is required. If a wound is small and uncontaminated, then a tetanus booster is recommended only if it has been more than 10 years since the last tetanus dose. However, in complicated, large or contaminated wounds, a tetanus booster is recommended if it has been more than 5 years since the last tetanus dose. Therefore as his wound is contaminated, \u003Cstrong\u003Eflucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID \u003C/strong\u003Ealone is not the correct answer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst prophylactic antibiotics are recommended for this patient, oral antibiotics would be sufficient for this patient and therefore \u003Cstrong\u003ECefazolin 2 g IV TDS \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate response. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetanus Immunoglobulin and flucloxacillin 500 mg PO QID \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003EAdsorbed diphtheria and tetanus (ADT) vaccine and Tetanus Immunoglobulin \u003C/strong\u003Eare\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Enot the most appropriate responses as tetanus immunoglobulin is only indicated if less than three doses of the vaccine have been given and if the wound is anything other than a small and clean wound.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The type of wound determines at what interval a tetanus booster is required.","If the wound is tetanus-prone (complicated, large or contaminated wounds), then a tetanus booster is required if more than 5 years since the last booster."],"references":["Tetanus. In: The Immunisation Handbook [online]. 2023. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/tetanus","Post-traumatic wound infections. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. 2019; cited 2022 Jun. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Prevaldi C, Paolillo C, Locatelli C, Ricci G, Catena F, Ansaloni L, Cervellin G. Management of traumatic wounds in the Emergency Department: position paper from the Academy of Emergency Medicine and Care (AcEMC) and the World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES). World J Emerg Surg. 2016;;11:30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27330546/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46894"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46894"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T14:47:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T14:47:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61443"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating"